 class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100656"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827285?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Meta Platforms 提议要求所有欧洲用户根据他们与 Instagram 等应用程序的互动方式来决定是否愿意看到有针对性的广告。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：托马斯·怀特/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100656"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sam-schechner" itemprop="url" rel="author">萨姆·谢赫纳</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 7:40（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-offers-to-seek-consent-for-highly-personalized-ads-in-europe-b520cbeb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Instagram 可能很快就会征求您的许可，然后再利用您尴尬的舞蹈视频习惯来选择您看到的广告（前提是您住在欧洲）。</p><p>在隐私监管机构的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/metas-facebook-needs-consent-to-personalize-ads-eu-court-rules-6c705f18?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">压力下</a>， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a>提议要求欧洲所有用户根据他们与公司应用程序的互动方式（例如他们观看的视频或分享的帖子）来决定是否愿意看到有针对性的广告。</p><p>知情人士称，该公司在向隐私监管机构提交的一份提案中表示，它可能会更新其系统，最快在 10 月底就此类广告寻求同意，以结束欧盟<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/metas-targeted-ad-model-faces-restrictions-in-europe-11670335772?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">长达一年的有关这些广告合法性的争论。</a>该提案称。</p><p>将所谓的行为广告限制在选择加入的用户范围内的提议远远超出了 Meta 迄今为止针对隐私监管机构所做的回应。自四月份以来，Meta 允许欧洲用户根据其在 Meta 应用程序中的活动<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-to-let-users-opt-out-of-some-targeted-ads-but-only-in-europe-44b20b6d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">请求选择退出</a>广告，但前提是用户在其帮助页面上填写了一份冗长的表格。这一过程可能限制了选择退出的人数。</p><p>相比之下，寻求同意需要在展示此类广告之前要求用户说“是”或“否”。根据欧盟法律，即使用户拒绝，也必须能够访问该服务。</p><p>对广告收入的打击可能会很大。如果大量用户根据自己在 Instagram 或 Facebook 上的活动拒绝广告，Meta 的系统最终将获得更少的信号来推断兴趣并为构成其大部分收入的广告建立受众群体。这可能会降低其广告效果，从而影响价格。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=D340813E-FD24-4A69-98A6-4EDEFF32F1C7&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmeta-offers-to-seek-consent-for-highly-personalized-ads-in-europe-b520cbeb&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">自从 Lina Khan 于 2021 年成为联邦贸易委员会主席以来，她一直在与 Meta、微软和亚马逊较量，这让她成为了争议的避雷针。 《华尔街日报》详细分析了她所选择的战斗以及她愿意失败的原因。图片插图：沉星培<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Meta 并未公布其来自欧盟的收入，但它可能占据了更广泛的欧洲地区的大部分收入，其中还包括英国和土耳其。该公司表示，第二季度其<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-platforms-facebook-q2-earnings-report-2023-a0297b9c" target="_blank" class="icon none">315 亿美元的广告收入中</a>有 23% 来自欧洲地区。</p><p> Meta 报告称，得益于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-platforms-facebook-q2-earnings-report-2023-a0297b9c" target="_blank" class="icon none">利用人工智能</a>改善广告定位，今年其广告收入出现反弹。这帮助该公司从<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="company-name">苹果 iPhone</a>隐私变更导致的 100 亿美元<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/facebook-feels-10-billion-sting-from-apples-privacy-push-11643898139?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">广告收入下降</a>中恢复过来。这些于 2021 年进行的更改阻碍了 Meta 使用其拥有的有关用户在第三方应用程序上的活动的数据的能力。如果没有 Meta 自己的应用程序的使用数据，目前尚不清楚这些人工智能修复将如何执行。</p><p> Meta 表示，计划在爱尔兰数据保护委员会的讨论和指导后做出同意的变更。爱尔兰数据保护委员会是该公司的主要隐私监管机构，因为该公司的欧盟总部位于爱尔兰。该公司补充说，改变后广告商仍然能够在欧洲开展个性化广告活动。</p><p> Meta 提议对行为广告征求同意的修改开启了一场争议的新篇章，这一争议可以追溯到 2018 年，当时欧盟的隐私法《通用数据保护法》生效。当时，Meta 使用其服务条款来证明根据用户在其应用程序中的活动选择广告的合理性。选择很明确： <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stage-is-set-for-battle-over-data-privacy-in-europe-1526031104" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">同意服务条款</a>，或停止使用该应用程序。</p><p>隐私活动人士马克斯·施雷姆斯(Max Schrems)对此提出了抱怨，他发起了一项诉讼，最终于去年提交给所有欧盟隐私监管机构的委员会。去年 12 月，他们决定 Meta 不能利用<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/metas-targeted-ad-model-faces-restrictions-in-europe-11670335772?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">其服务条款协议</a>来证明这些广告的合理性。爱尔兰数据保护委员会于 1 月份下令停止这样做，并处<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-fined-more-than-400-million-for-sending-ads-based-on-online-activity-11672844441" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">以约 4.3 亿美元的罚款</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C88AF8C6-9381-4531-8397-8E3466D42127&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmeta-offers-to-seek-consent-for-highly-personalized-ads-in-europe-b520cbeb&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Twitter 所有者埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk) 和 Meta 首席执行官马克·扎克伯格 (Mark Zuckerberg) 已同意进行笼式比赛。肢体冲突可能是第一次，但《华尔街日报》的乔安娜·斯特恩在动作玩偶的帮助下解释了为什么这场科技斗殴实际上就像过去的硅谷争吵一样。照片插图：Kenny Wassus、Preston Jessee<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Meta 对这一决定提出上诉，但在 4 月份也将其行为广告的法律依据改为欧盟隐私法的一项条款，该条款援引了其业务的“合法利益”。作为这一变化的一部分，它创建了在线表单，让用户可以选择请求退出行为广告。</p><p>随后，欧盟最高法院出人意料地介入了。在 7 月份的一项主要针对不同主题的裁决中，法院表示，用户对自己隐私的兴趣凌驾于 Facebook 等社交网络展示行为广告的“合法利益”论点之上，除非<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/metas-facebook-needs-consent-to-personalize-ads-eu-court-rules-6c705f18?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">它已征得用户同意</a>。</p><p>做出该决定后，爱尔兰隐私监管机构告诉 Meta，它不遵守 1 月份的决定，并转达了其他一些欧洲隐私监管机构的反对意见。例如，挪威上个月要求 Meta 停止在欧洲展示行为广告，直到获得同意为止。</p><p>知情人士称，Meta 最近几天告诉监管机构，它愿意转而寻求同意，但表示这一改变是一个重大障碍，至少需要三个月的时间才能实施。</p><p>该公司还表示，有可能等到明年初实施该计划，同时与旨在促进竞争的单独欧盟法规相关的变化同时实施，该法规要求公司核心服务之间的数据混合需要获得同意。</p><p>写信给 Sam Schechner： <a href="mailto:Sam.Schechner@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Sam.Schechner@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 11:40:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-offers-to-seek-consent-for-highly-personalized-ads-in-europe-b520cbeb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-offers-to-seek-consent-for-highly-personalized-ads-in-europe-b520cbeb<author><![CDATA[Sam Schechner]]></author><category>专有的</category><category>广告服务</category><category>数字营销服务</category><category>市场研究/公共关系</category><category>公共关系</category><category>广告/营销/公共关系</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>营销服务</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>隐私问题/信息安全</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>元平台</category><category>梅塔</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>隐私问题</category><category>信息安全</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>广告服务</category><category>数字营销服务</category><category>市场调查</category><category>公共关系</category><category>广告</category><category>营销</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>营销服务</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[TSA’s New Tech Can Make Airport Screening Faster. Travelers Aren’t So Sure.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>乘客们指责新的扫描仪减慢了他们的速度； TSA 表示人群是一个更重要的因素<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098556"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826797?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乘客正在学习如何操作 CT 扫描仪，就像迈阿密国际机场所示的扫描仪一样。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔·雷德尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098556"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/allison-pohle" itemprop="url" rel="author">艾莉森·波尔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 7:05 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-tsas-new-tech-can-make-airport-screening-faster-travelers-arent-so-sure-b49eec89"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>机场安检处的新型扫描仪可以更好地检测爆炸物和潜在威胁，而且它们还可以让您将笔记本电脑放在随身携带的包中。乘客们表示， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/could-more-convenient-airport-security-be-around-the-corner-1499870669?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">新机器</a>也导致等待时间更长。</p><p>美国运输安全管理局表示，其计算机断层扫描仪 (CT) 将使机场安检变得更强大、更快，并认为新机器的使用不会让检查站的等待时间更长。现在，美国 228 个机场中的机器可以创建行李内容的 3D 图像，同时减少对行李进行额外搜查的旅客数量。他们需要一些时间来适应，因为乘客正在学习将所有物品放入宽而扁平的垃圾箱中，而不是将行李直接放在传送带上。</p><p>在极少数情况下，在 CT 扫描仪前等待会导致乘客错过航班，经常乘坐飞机的乘客表示，他们比平时更早到达机场，以避免发生意外。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823499?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> TSA 的新型 CT 扫描仪可创建随身行李的 3D 图像，工作人员可以将其旋转 360 度。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔·雷德尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/airport-travel-tips-flight-summer-a6771549?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">繁忙的夏季</a>和新设备的结合是美国机场面临的最新挑战，美国机场通过安全检查站的旅客数量创历史新高。 TSA 官员现在建议旅客在航班起飞前两到三个小时到达机场。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> TSA 负责人 David Pekoske 表示，新扫描仪一旦准备就绪，就会立即安装，而不是等待淡季。他说，情报官员告诉美国运输安全管理局，这项技术已经用于托运行李，也需要尽快用于随身行李。</p><p> “一年中机场不繁忙的时间很少，”他说。</p><p> TSA 拥有近 750 台 CT 机扫描随身行李，今年迄今已安装 180 台。作为迄今为止耗资 3.41 亿美元升级的一部分，该国不到一半的机场安检通道配备了扫描仪。该机构表示，目标是让所有乘客将笔记本电脑和一些液体放在行李中。</p><p>当袋子进入机器时，CT 扫描仪会创建袋子的 3D 图像。工作人员可以旋转图像以进行更彻底的检查，而无需打开行李或将乘客叫到一边。 TSA 官员表示，虽然图像生成和分析可能比旧 X 光机花费的时间更长，但新技术<strong>&nbsp;</strong>并没有改变总体等待时间。</p><p>丹佛大都会州立大学航空安全教授杰弗里·普莱斯 (Jeffrey Price) 表示：“运输安全管理局在适应这项新技术的过程中面临着巨大的学习曲线。”他说，特工现在从扫描中收到更多信息，这意味着他们正在重新学习如何分析图像。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="2062" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/2837043c-072b-4f82-9804-8277fd799d76-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><h3>乘客学习曲线</h3><p>乘客也有一个学习曲线。几位 TSA 工作人员表示，如果鞋子、帽子和其他松散物品没有安全地放入垃圾箱中，它们可能会掉下来并卡在机器中。</p><p> TSA 监控检查站的等待时间，并制定了可接受的标准——标准安检通道为 30 分钟或更少，预检查为 10 分钟。 TSA 表示，目前的等待时间在这些限制之内。 （Pekoske 表示，当 PreCheck 等待时间超过 15 分钟时，他会收到通知。）</p><p>来自印第安纳州曼西的经常出差的马特·坎茨 (Matt Kantz) 表示，他正在为机场安检争取额外的时间，比平常提前 30 分钟离开。这位 50 岁的销售总监定期飞往印第安纳波利斯，他说自从今年早些时候安装了 CT 机器以来，在 TSA PreCheck 通道上等待的时间更长了。他说，4 月和 5 月各一次通过 PreCheck 通道需要 20 多分钟。</p><p>第一次，他说他差点错过了航班。 “现在的情况和过去的情况之间存在着明显的区别，”他说。</p><p> TSA 表示，今年春天，由于安装机器，等待时间比正常情况要长，但表示其数据与 Kantz 的账户不符。该机构还指出，印第安纳波利斯机场的旅客量创历史新高。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=36242EF1-64E6-49CF-80F3-CDC344685AFE&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-tsas-new-tech-can-make-airport-screening-faster-travelers-arent-so-sure-b49eec89&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">传统航空公司和低成本航空公司在规划航线网络时使用不同的模型。我们请联合航空公司的全球网络规划人员解释该流程的运作方式以及每种策略的优缺点。照片插图：Nayon Cho<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>技术升级</h3><p>多名 TSA 代理表示，该扫描仪品牌 Analogic 会在某些物品通过时离线，需要重新启动系统并导致停机。特工们要求不透露姓名，以讨论他们的角色细节。</p><p> Analogic 高管将所有评论提交给 TSA。</p><p>今年夏天早些时候，德克萨斯州拉伯克·普雷斯顿·史密斯国际机场的官员警告旅客，新的 CT 扫描仪会缩短等待时间，并导致一些人错过航班。</p><p>起初，这些机器每周都会离线几次，说</p>查克·法里纳（Chuck Farina），机场运营和安全副总监。他说，这种情况现在已经很少发生了，但即使是几分钟的停机时间来重置机器也会在高峰时段减慢乘客的速度。<p></p><p>佩科斯克表示，运输安全管理局拥有训练有素的安全人员来重置机器。该机构还在更新扫描仪的软件。</p><h3>机场体验</h3><p>机场负责人表示，随着乘客和工作人员的调整，等待时间将会缩短，并指出安检后无需重新打包行李是一个优势。</p><p>北卡罗来纳州阿什维尔地区机场管理局总裁兼首席执行官卢·布莱韦斯 (Lew Bleiweis) 表示：“扫描过程较长，但在检查站之后就不再进行重新组合。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您是否经历过更长的 TSA 等待时间？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> TSA 官员表示，在亚特兰大，CT 系统的等待时间更短。二次袋子筛选也更具针对性，因为特工不再需要在袋子里翻找。</p><p>锡拉丘兹地区机场管理局执行董事 Jason Terreri 表示，自从引进 CT 机器以来，锡拉丘兹汉考克国际机场的等待时间有所改善。他说，在某些情况下，乘客会从 TSA 预检通道移至标准安检通道，因为等待时间较短。</p><h3>未来的改进</h3><p>乘客们表示，当他们在安检通道尽头等待行李时，他们的等待感最为强烈。但佩科斯克说，他们没有计算他们花了多少时间重新包装这些袋子。</p><p> “当我在做某事时，我觉得时间过得更快一点，”他说。 “当我只是在等待某些东西从隧道中出来时，例如 X 光检查，那段时间对我来说似乎更长。”</p><p> TSA 表示，未来事情会变得更快。现在，特工坐在机器旁边监视每一个行李。该机构正在测试一种远程筛查选项，该选项可以将图像从多个通道发送到一个独立的房间进行审查，以提高效率。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826944?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">锡拉丘兹国际机场是近年来变得更加繁忙的众多小型机场之一。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：iStock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给 Allison Pohle，邮箱为<a href="mailto:allison.pohle@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">allison.pohle@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 11:05:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-tsas-new-tech-can-make-airport-screening-faster-travelers-arent-so-sure-b49eec89</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-tsas-new-tech-can-make-airport-screening-faster-travelers-arent-so-sure-b49eec89<author><![CDATA[Allison Pohle]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>机场</category><category>航空运输</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>机场</category><category>航空运输</category><category>运输</category><category>后勤</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Companies Weigh Growing Power of Cloud Providers Amid AI Boom]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>人工智能模型制造商和云提供商之间的一波合作浪潮正在引导技术主管评估便利性与过度依赖任何一家供应商的好处<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098911"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826696?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">企业技术领导者表示，他们对生成人工智能的选择可能会产生长期影响，包括成本。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：ALY Song/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098911"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/belle-lin" itemprop="url" rel="author">林贝儿</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 7:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/companies-weigh-growing-power-of-cloud-providers-amid-ai-boom-478c454a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>想要部署生成式人工智能的公司需要做出一些选择。</p><p>有许多大型语言模型为生成式人工智能提供动力，许多制造这些模型的人工智能公司都与大型云计算供应商建立了合作伙伴关系。当商业技术领导者在其中做出选择时，他们正在权衡使用一家云提供商的人工智能生态系统的风险和收益。</p><p>他们表示，这是一个重要的决定，可能会产生长期后果，包括他们花费了多少资金，以及他们是否愿意更深入地研究云提供商的一套软件、工具和服务。</p><p>到目前为止，OpenAI、Anthropic 和 Cohere 等人工智能模型制造商在开发专有的大型语言模型方面处于领先地位，公司使用这些模型来提高<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/businesses-cfo-aim-to-harness-generative-ai-to-shake-up-accounting-finance-f427ff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">会计</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/generative-ai-helping-boost-productivity-of-some-software-developers-731fa5a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">编写代码</a>等领域的效率，或者使用<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/instacart-joins-chatgpt-frenzy-adding-chatbot-to-grocery-shopping-app-bc8a2d3c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">自定义聊天机器人</a>等工具将其添加到自己的产品中。</p><p>模型制造商与主要云公司之间的合作包括<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsoft-and-openai-forge-awkward-partnership-as-techs-new-power-couple-3092de51?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">OpenAI 和 Microsoft Azure</a> 、Anthropic 和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-in-talks-to-invest-200-million-into-ai-startup-11666381180?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Cohere 与 Google Cloud</a>以及机器学习初创公司 Hugging Face 与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="company-name">Amazon</a> Web Services 的合作。数据存储和管理公司 Databricks 于 6 月同意<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/databricks-strikes-1-3-billion-deal-for-generative-ai-startup-mosaicml-fdcefc06?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">收购生成型人工智能初创公司 MosaicML</a> 。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826689?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Adnan Masood，数字技术和 IT 服务公司 UST 的首席人工智能架构师。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：科技大学</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>顾问、数字技术和信息技术服务公司首席人工智能架构师 Adnan Masood 表示，对于许多企业来说，首要选择不是使用哪种人工智能模型，而是是否留在云提供商提供的人工智能生态系统中。美国科技大学。 Masood 表示，这家总部位于加利福尼亚州亚里索维耶霍的公司开始使用 OpenAI 及其云合作伙伴 Microsoft Azure 的人工智能模型，部分原因是该公司已经在微软的云平台上运行。</p><p>不过，总部位于休斯敦的 BMC Software 首席技术官 Ram Chakravarti 表示，如果一家公司选择单一的人工智能生态系统，它可能会面临“供应商锁定”在该提供商平台和服务集内的风险。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong>这种范式是一种反复出现的范式，即企业的 IT 系统、软件和数据<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-tech-rule-could-complicate-cio-cloud-strategy-experts-say-11657644239?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">都位于一个数字平台中</a>，并且随着公司寻求使用生成式人工智能的帮助，这种范式可能会变得更加明显。</p><p>公司表示，供应商锁定的问题，尤其是云提供商之间的问题是，他们很难将数据转移到其他平台，失去与其他供应商的谈判能力，并且必须依赖一个提供商来保证其服务在线且安全。</p><p>云提供商现在提供工具来帮助客户在自己的平台和竞争对手的平台之间移动数据，部分原因是为了应对锁定的抱怨。企业越来越多地<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/battle-for-the-cloud-once-amazon-vs-microsoft-now-has-many-fronts-11627221600?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与多家云提供商签约</a>，以减少对任何单一供应商的依赖。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827180?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ram Chakravarti，BMC Software 首席技术官。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：BMC 软件</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>查克拉瓦蒂说，这就是公司最终可能对生成式人工智能采取的策略，通过使用“多种生成式人工智能方法”，他们可以避免在特定平台上过于根深蒂固。可以肯定的是，许多首席信息官表示，他们愿意接受此类风险，因为与单一技术供应商或云提供商合作会带来便利，并可能降低成本。</p><p>分析师表示，融入生成式人工智能的一个重大挑战是该技术变化如此之快，迫使首席信息官不仅<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/companies-are-drowning-in-too-much-ai-1c27c003?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">要跟上创新的步伐</a>，还要<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/generative-ai-pilots-have-companies-reaching-for-the-guardrails-4326704c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">筛选潜在的数据隐私和网络安全风险</a>。</p><p> Masood 表示，一家公司使用其云提供商的预制工具和服务，加上保护公司数据和减少不准确输出的护栏，可以更快地实施现成的生成式人工智能。</p><p> “它有隐私，有安全性，有所有合规要素，”他说。 “到那时，人们实际上不必太担心事物的物流，而是专注于利用该模型。”</p><p>表示，对于其他公司来说，将生成式人工智能与他们已经信任的大型云平台一起使用来保存敏感的公司数据是一种保守的方法。</p> Jon Turow，Madrona Venture Group 合伙人。 “对话的开始是很自然的，‘嘿，你也想在我的四堵墙内应用人工智能吗？’”<p></p><p>人工智能公司 AI21 联合创始人 Ori Goshen 表示，虽然许多公司表示他们希望利用自己的数据“微调”或定制大型语言模型，但大多数公司发现他们不需要进行此类投资。实验室。他说，许多客户只是在寻找一种方法来提出问题并根据他们的数据撰写摘要，而 AI21 提供自己的软件来帮助客户部署其模型。</p><p> “你可以从概念上将这些语言模型视为引擎，但基本上公司想要的是汽车，”他说。 “我们让您离汽车更近了。”</p><p>对于云提供商来说，这也是一个利用生成式人工智能来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsoft-google-amazon-look-to-generative-ai-to-lift-cloud-businesses-7159a43f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">提高对其核心云服务需求</a>的机会。微软<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsoft-msft-q4-earnings-report-2023-3d6ebe64?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">上周公布</a>季度销售增长放缓，尽管人工智能带来的兴奋提振了其业务。谷歌的云计算部门是其人工智能战略的核心部分，上周<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/alphabet-google-googl-q2-earnings-report-2023-f3cb023?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">公布的收入为 80 亿美元</a>，同比增长 28%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827172?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Swami Sivasubramanian，AWS 数据和机器学习副总裁。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：诺亚·伯格/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>亚马逊预计将于周四公布财报，上周宣布更新其 Bedrock AI 平台，使企业能够更轻松地提取自己的数据以用于大型语言模型，并部署<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-joins-microsoft-google-in-ai-race-spurred-by-chatgpt-d7c34738?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">AWS 支持的各种 AI 模型</a>。 Swami Sivasubramanian，该公司数据和机器学习副总裁。</p><p>与 AWS 一样，谷歌云越来越致力于将自己打造成一个中立的平台，开发人员可以在其中选择来自不同公司的一系列生成式人工智能模型。公司发言人表示，它支持自己的模型，如 PaLM，以及其他开源、第三方和定制模型。</p><p> Sivasubramanian 表示，客户希望自己选择人工智能模型，通常会使用多个人工智能模型来实现单一功能，最终“构建了太多的脚手架”来让它们工作，以至于他们需要额外的帮助。</p><p>微软<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-and-microsoft-team-up-to-distribute-new-ai-software-for-commercial-use-c4f7b634?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">上个月宣布</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="">Meta</a><span class="company-name-type">的</span>开源 Llama 2 模型将免费提供给使用其云平台的开发人员，并表示它还允许开发人员构建自己的基于人工智能的“副驾驶”工作助手，并且公司可以提取自己的数据来与 OpenAI 模型一起使用。</p><p>理论上，这些合作伙伴关系开启了首席信息官可以在公司内部使用的人工智能模型的数量和种类。但一些技术领导者仍然不想与单一云或技术提供商保持联系，并决定等待，看看哪些人工智能模型可以以最优惠的价格提供最佳性能。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “我们将利用我们目前拥有的标准技术堆栈和基础设施，即带有 OpenAI 的 Microsoft Azure，”生物制药服务公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SYNH" class="">Syneos Health</a>的首席信息和数字官 Larry Pickett 表示<span class="company-name-type">。</span> “但我们知道这有点像所有这些不同竞争对手之间的赛马，所以我们只想保持灵活性。”</p><p>安永全球首席创新官 Jeff Wong 等其他人正在测试尽可能多的人工智能模型，以确定每种工具的优点和缺点。 “我们基本上正在与所有即将到来的人会面，而且名单每天都在变化，”黄说。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JNJ" class="">强生公司首席信息官吉姆·斯旺森</a>(Jim Swanson) 表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span>该医疗保健产品公司正在使用“几个主要供应商”来测试各种人工智能模型，其中包括来自 OpenAI 的模型。</p><p> “不会只有一种大型语言模型能够赢得所有人的青睐，尽管广告最多的可能是 ChatGPT，”Swanson 说道<strong>，</strong>他指的是 OpenAI 基于其大型语言模型的聊天机器人。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——伊莎贝尔·布斯克特对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Belle Lin： <a href="mailto:belle.lin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">belle.lin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/companies-weigh-grinding-power-of-cloud-providers-amid-ai-boom-478c454a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/companies-weigh-grinding-power-of-cloud-providers-amid-ai-boom-478c454a<author><![CDATA[Belle Lin]]></author><category>人工智能技术</category><category>计算机服务</category><category>云计算</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>数据服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>伙伴关系/合作</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>元平台</category><category>梅塔</category><category>Syneos 健康</category><category>同步号</category><category>强生公司</category><category>强生</category><category>微软</category><category>微软公司</category><category>元</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>伙伴关系</category><category>合作</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>计算机服务</category><category>云计算</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>数据服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Put ‘Great Sex’ on Your Vacation To-Do List]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>假期性爱可能是与伴侣重新建立联系的绝佳方式，但有时期望与现实不符<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825716/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>插图：Andrea Mongia<span>插图：Andrea Mongia</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098092"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098092"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/elizabeth-anne-bernstein"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://si.wsj.net/public/resources/images/CH-AA158_Bernst_NS_20100111195708.gif" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/elizabeth-anne-bernstein" itemprop="url" rel="author">伊丽莎白·伯恩斯坦</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日晚上 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/put-great-sex-on-your-vacation-to-do-list-198da577"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>马特·休斯 (Matt Hughes) 希望一切都完美，以庆祝他的结婚十周年纪念日。他带妻子去了一家豪华度假村的海滨套房，并送来了鲜花、巧克力和香槟。当晚，夫妻俩去一家法国餐厅吃饭。</p><p>当他们回到自己的房间时，休斯调暗了灯光，倾身亲吻——然后听到一声巨大的汪汪声。</p><p>隔壁房间里有几只狗开始吠叫。这对夫妇试图继续前进，但事实证明这些狗太分散了他们的注意力。前台没有提供太多帮助；房间里的人类踪影全无。</p><p> After several hours, Hughes, 53 years old, a technology executive from San Clemente, Calif., drove to a pharmacy and bought earplugs. “It was really frustrating,” he said.</p><p> What is it they say about best-laid plans? (Pun intended.)</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-workers-are-finally-taking-guilt-free-vacations-f5eb383f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Vacation</a> sex can be an excellent way for us to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/right-mood-wrong-time-get-back-in-sync-in-the-bedroom-11675744215?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">reconnect with our partner</a> —and create memories we can draw on in the future. We&#39;re already focused on pleasure and adventure. The novelty of a new place can be arousing. Without the distraction of our daily responsibilities, we <em>should</em> have more time to make it happen.</p><p> Sadly, reality often intervenes. Noisy hotels, sunburn, hangovers and the boss who just won&#39;t let go can put a damper on things. These days, there&#39;s a more overarching problem, too: Many of us live in such a state of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stress-relief-walk-nature-science-11659388504?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">chronic stress</a> that our nervous systems are stuck on high alert. Even when we get away from our day-to-day worries, we&#39;re irritable, exhausted, unable to relax.</p><p> That&#39;s not sexy!</p><p> In reporting this column, I heard from readers about their vacation-sex challenges.</p><p> “My husband and I are laughing at your email. We are currently on vacation with 6 kids,” one woman responded.</p><p> “We stopped to have sex on a mossy patch while on a motorcycle trip, but the bugs, rocks and general outdoor reality really killed the mood,” said another.</p><p> “I got food poisoning,” said a man, who explained that his ex-girlfriend didn&#39;t fully grasp how sick he was. “This might have been taken personally, which might have led to our end.”</p><p> Research on sexual fantasies demonstrates our desire for a romantic interlude. Ninety percent of people have fantasized about sex in a hotel; 85% about sex in nature; 83% about sex on the beach or another exotic location, and 53% about sex on an airplane, according to</p> Justin Lehmiller, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-tech-will-change-sex-and-intimacy-for-better-and-worse-11615003201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a social psychologist</a> and research fellow at Indiana University&#39;s Kinsey Institute, who <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-kinseys-75-years-of-sex-research-says-about-us-11662464272?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">conducted the studies</a> .<p></p><p> Anticipation is a big part of the fun. It also can be part of the problem. We often imagine that a future event will be much better (or worse) than it turns out to be. Researchers call this affective forecasting. When it comes to vacation sex, high hopes can create pressure, which can kill the mood.</p><p> “If you feel you have to do something, then immediately you want it less,” says Amanda Luterman, a psychotherapist in Montreal, who specializes in sexual relationships.</p><p> If sex doesn&#39;t happen, it can feel not just disappointing but hurtful. One partner might feel rejected or taken for granted. Both might feel like failures who have squandered a wonderful opportunity—and spent a lot of money doing it.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Are you able to have good vacation sex? Why or why not?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Hughes and his wife, married 22 years, have had vacation-romance mishaps other than barking dogs. On a Caribbean trip years ago, their kids came down with hand, foot and mouth disease on the one night they had a babysitter. Last year in Italy, their daughter got Covid and the family quarantined. In Puerto Vallarta in July, they planned an evening alone in their room, but couldn&#39;t relax knowing that the kids—now teenagers—were at the hotel&#39;s pool bar likely having their first drinks. (Mexico&#39;s legal drinking age is 18.)</p><p> Hughes says he sometimes doubts himself when intimacy doesn&#39;t pan out on a trip. “I wonder, &#39;Are you really that into me?&#39;” he says.</p><p> So he&#39;s developed vacation strategies to keep the fire lit. He tries to stay flexible and keep the mood relaxing. He indulges his kids. (“Happy kids, happy mom.”) He also looks for fun activities he and his wife can do that are outside their comfort zone. In Mexico, the couple went disco dancing.</p><p> “I think the best way to focus on sex is not to,” Hughes says. “When people feel at ease and relaxed, the thing that you want to happen comes naturally.”</p><p> How can you make sure satisfying vacation sex actually happens? It may take some planning.这里有一些建议。</p><h3> Schedule regular vacations.</h3><p> Put them on your calendar. This will give you more opportunities for a vacation-sex reset, as well as something to look forward to.</p><h3> Talk about expectations.</h3><p> Start with the vacation itself: What activities do you want to do, how much time together do you need, should there be limitations on work and screens? “This will help reduce opportunities for resentment,” says Marissa Nelson, a sex therapist in Washington, DC</p><p> Then talk about intimacy, including what makes you feel closer to your partner and any new activities you might like to try. Discuss what to do if things don&#39;t go as planned. Public Service Announcement: Try another time.</p><h3> Don&#39;t overplan.</h3><p> If you&#39;ve got every hour mapped out, you&#39;ll wear yourself out. You also won&#39;t have time to be spontaneous. Spontaneity is sexy, Lehmiller says.</p><h3> Don&#39;t hustle up until the last moment.</h3><p> Pack early. Finish up work and errands with time to spare. “You dramatically increase your chances of a satisfying sexual and emotional connection by priming your nervous system before your departure,” says Julia DiGangi, a neuropsychologist in Chicago.</p><h3> Be adventurous.</h3><p> Start outside of bed. Go somewhere new, or try an activity or food you haven&#39;t tried before. New experiences activate our brain&#39;s reward system, flooding it with neurochemicals related to pleasure and bonding—the same circuits triggered when we first fall in love.</p><p> Shake it up in the bedroom, too. (Even a new time of day counts.) “Vacations are about exploration,” Nelson says.</p><h3> Staycations count.</h3><p> Sneak away close to home sometime. Even one night is enough to reset, if you get in a vacation mode of mind, Lehmiller says.</p><p> Think of it as a “laycation,” Mike Dowd, an architect in Portland, Ore., told me. “It&#39;s a vacation where you stay home and hope to have sex,” he says.</p><p> Write to Elizabeth Bernstein at <a href="mailto:Elizabeth.Bernstein@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Elizabeth.Bernstein@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> more bonds columns</h4><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/these-chirping-sounds-can-soothe-your-anxiety-7bb6e809?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Birds Are the Secret Weapon in Your Fight Against Anxiety</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/float-tanks-health-benefits-stress-d844e4ba?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">When Finding Your Bliss Means Floating, Naked</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/celebrating-mothers-day-after-your-mom-is-gone-af4b84d6?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Coping With Mother&#39;s Day When You&#39;re Grieving</a></li></ul></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/put-great-sex-on-your-vacation-to-do-list-198da577</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/put-great-sex-on-your-vacation-to-do-list-198da577<author><![CDATA[Elizabeth Bernstein]]></author><category> wsjlifework</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>IWE Filter</category><category> Personal Announcements</category><category> Routine General News</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>iwe filter</category><category> personal announcements</category><category> routine general news</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Miami Sees Its First Population Drop in Decades]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Soaring housing costs drive many locals away despite economic boom <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823690/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Miami-Dade County’s population shrank between 2019 and 2022, its first population loss over a multiyear period since at least 1970." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Miami-Dade County&#39;s population shrank between 2019 and 2022, its first population loss over a multiyear period since at least 1970. Saul Martinez/Bloomberg News <span>Saul Martinez/Bloomberg News</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098188"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098188"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/konrad-putzier" itemprop="url" rel="author">Konrad Putzier</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/deborah-acosta" itemprop="url" rel="author">Deborah Acosta</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 9:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/miami-sees-its-first-population-drop-in-decades-e181171f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Miami, a global hot spot with ambitions to be a business and financial hub, is driving away more residents than it is attracting.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/miami-locals-are-steamed-over-relocating-new-yorkers-driving-up-apartment-rents-11652175000?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Surging housing costs</a> and a fickle labor market, which by one measure still hasn&#39;t recovered from the pandemic, are sending many locals packing. Miami-Dade lost 79,535 people through net migration to other parts of Florida or other states between 2020 and 2022, according to an <a href="https://www.brookings.edu/articles/pandemic-driven-population-declines-in-large-urban-areas-are-slowing-or-reversing-latest-census-data-shows/" target="_blank" class="icon none">analysis of US Census Bureau data</a> by the Brookings Institution. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826058?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Although foreign immigration offset some of the loss and helped the county&#39;s population rise slightly last year, Miami-Dade County&#39;s population still shrank between 2019 and 2022—its first population loss over a multiyear period since at least 1970, according to the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis.</p><p> The population loss in the state&#39;s largest county stands in contrast to the rest of Florida, which added more people between 2021 and 2022 than any other state.</p><p> Home prices in Miami have soared 53% since June 2020, according to online listing site <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/Z" class="">Zillow</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> the second most out of the top 50 metropolitan housing markets after Tampa. The median asking rent has increased by 27% since 2019, according to data company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CSGP" class="">CoStar</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> rising despite the shrinking population because of a chronic shortage of affordable rental housing. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826059?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> It is easy to spot ways in which the city is booming. Major boulevards are littered with construction cranes and Miami office towers have a lower vacancy rate than other major US cities. Miami-Dade County&#39;s unemployment rate is well below the national average and it is creating new businesses at its fastest pace ever.</p><p> But Miami risks following the same path as New York City and San Francisco, the country&#39;s financial and tech centers, where the growth of high-paying white collar jobs raised the cost of living, sending many of those cities&#39; working and middle-class residents searching for a more affordable place to live.</p><p> Despite the economic boom, Miami-Dade has experienced a bigger loss as a share of total population than the city of Baltimore and Wayne County, Mich., which includes Detroit, over the two-year period.</p><p> “It&#39;s the middle class, it&#39;s our talent base, it&#39;s our college graduates moving out for better opportunities elsewhere,” said Maria Ilcheva, census information center lead at Florida International University&#39;s Jorge M. Perez Metropolitan Center. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823731?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Miami-Dade lost 79,535 people through net migration to other parts of Florida or other states between 2020 and 2022.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: James Jackman for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Jose Perez,</p> a real-estate broker who was born and raised in Miami, is among those who felt priced out. More than half his clients left the area when the cost of living began to soar. With incomes of between $70,000 and $150,000, they were living paycheck to paycheck, he said.<p></p><p> Perez soon moved out himself. He sold his Miami home for $800,000 and bought a comparable one in the central Florida city Ocala for $297,000. His savings in insurance alone add up to $5,460 a year, he said. His property taxes went from $7000 to under $2000 a year.</p><p> “Here you see you can get so much more bang for your buck,” said Perez, who now works for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DHI" class="">DR Horton</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> a national home builder.</p><p> Miami was already one of the country&#39;s least affordable metropolitan areas before the pandemic, which helped drive prices up even more. The Miami metro area posted an annual consumer-price inflation of 6.9% in June, according to the US Bureau of Labor Statistics. That is more than double the national inflation. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1000" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826060?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The city also has the highest share of “cost-burdened renters” of any major metropolitan area: 61% of its rental population are spending 30% or more of household income on housing, according to a report released this year by the Joint Center for Housing Studies at Harvard University.</p><p> High rents sting because the area&#39;s hourly wage, though rising, was below the national average as of 2022 and a far cry from earnings in New York and San Francisco.</p><p> While unemployment is low, the county&#39;s labor market by one measure lags behind the rest of the state. The total number of employed people in Miami-Dade County was slightly below 2019 levels in May while it has increased for Florida as a whole, according to data from the Florida Department of Economic Opportunity. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823506?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Construction crews work on the Legacy Residences development in Miami.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Scott McIntyre for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The area can&#39;t match the diverse economic base of cities like New York, and Miami also has struggled to match the success of sunbelt boomtowns like Phoenix and Austin in attracting factories and big corporate headquarters, which bring with them thousands of jobs.</p><p> Miami is attracting plenty of new companies. In 2022, 127,895 business applications were made in Miami-Dade County, according to the US Census Bureau. That was down slightly from the previous year, but well above prepandemic levels.</p><p> But many tech and finance firms are opening small or satellite offices that employ few people. Others are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/miamis-love-affair-with-crypto-is-souring-as-bitcoin-faithful-flock-to-the-city-9244f0d9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">focused on cryptocurrencies</a> , a market that has taken a nosedive.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What do you think are the future prospects of Miami?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Limited public transit and clogged roads also make it hard to entice employers. Hours lost to traffic delays in Miami increased by 59% between 2021 and 2022, according to data company INRIX—one of the highest increases among big US cities.</p><p> “We need to be a city that, below the skyline, can provide a good quality of living,” Ilcheva said.</p><p> Still, there are reasons for optimism. The influx of wealthy residents and rising property prices are boosting tax revenues and a recent surge in new construction could bring down housing costs over time. Rent growth has slowed and wages have increased.</p><p> Foreign immigration increased in 2022 from pandemic lows and helped offset some of the American exodus, though Miami-Dade county&#39;s population still shrank by 21,664 from 2020 to 2022 even with the rise in new residents from overseas. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823507?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Hours lost to traffic delays in Miami rose by 59% between 2021 and 2022, according to data company INRIX.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔·雷德尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Some Miami residents who left enjoy a lower cost of living but have been forced to make other trade-offs. Natalie Pena and her husband sold their 1,100 square foot home in Miami for $440,000. In June, they moved with their son to a larger home in Ocala, which they purchased for about half the price.</p><p> Still, she&#39;s had some trouble finding a job. Her husband, a barber, commutes 4½ hours to Miami early on Wednesdays to service his clients through Friday night. “I was expecting to take a hit, to reduce my salary, but it&#39;s been a little shocking,” she said.</p><p> Miami-Dade County&#39;s mayor last year declared a housing crisis, and rolled out several affordable housing initiatives and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/miami-offers-interest-free-loans-to-condo-owners-53189e9f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">other programs</a> . Gov. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">Ron DeSantis</a> recently signed legislation that will motivate developers to build workforce and affordable housing across the state to help address the housing crisis. The law, known as the “Live Local Act,” also prohibits local municipalities from enacting rent controls. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1200" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826895?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Miami-Dade County&#39;s population doubled between 1970 and 2010, but growth slowed over the past decade. At first, immigration from abroad masked the flow of people away from the region, Ilcheva said. A rise in outflows combined with lower immigration during the pandemic put the region&#39;s demographics into the red.</p><p> The top destinations for professionals leaving the Miami area are Orlando, Tampa Bay, Atlanta and Jacksonville, according to a recent LinkedIn study—all cities that also offer warm weather and low taxes, but much cheaper housing.</p><p> “The people who built this city cannot afford to live in their own homes that they spent their entire lives in,” said Billy Corben, a local resident and gadfly documentarian who often criticizes local politicians&#39; push for rapid growth. “Once those people are gone, then what is Miami? What is left of this place?” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823691?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Block 55 site in one of many buildings under construction in Miami.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Scott McIntyre for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Write to Konrad Putzier at <a href="mailto:konrad.putzier@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">konrad.putzier@wsj.com</a> and Deborah Acosta at <a href="mailto:deborah.acosta@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">deborah.acosta@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/miami-sees-its-first-population-drop-in-decades-e181171f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/miami-sees-its-first-population-drop-in-decades-e181171f<author><![CDATA[Konrad PutzierDeborah Acosta]]></author><category> wsj-usnews</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>Demographics</category><category> Real Estate/Property</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>demographics</category><category> real estate</category><category> property</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Catering to Your Midlife Crisis Is a Growing Business]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Budding industry helps adults who seek fulfilling second acts <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086694"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824308?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Increased longevity is leading more people to search for meaningful pursuits in their 40s, 50s and 60s.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: iStock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086694"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anne-tergesen" itemprop="url" rel="author">Anne Tergesen</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 10:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/midlife-crisis-money-business-companies-29dc2273"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Americans want their <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-virtuous-midlife-crisis-11578830400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">midlife crisis</a> to be more productive. This presents, for a growing number of companies, coaches and consultants, a multimillion-dollar opportunity.</p><p> Some programs are online and charge a couple hundred dollars. Others take place in exotic spots and feature luxury accommodations, yoga and surfing classes for thousands of dollars. Discounts are sometimes available.</p><p> Fueling the businesses are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/death-finances-and-how-many-of-us-get-our-money-needs-wrong-51a660a2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">longer lifespans</a> , leading more people to search for meaningful pursuits in their 40s, 50s and 60s. Some psychologists call this period a second adulthood when identity-shaping roles, from executive to full-time parent to caregiver, can fall away, causing some to re-evaluate.</p><p> “Transition is a skill we need to master in an era of increased longevity and change,” said Chip Conley, co-founder of Modern Elder Academy, or MEA, which offers online and in-person workshops. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824307?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Chip Conley, co-founder of Modern Elder Academy, in a white shirt, says ageism can cause people in midlife to believe they are irrelevant.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Modern Elder Academy</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Some studies show life satisfaction reaches a low point around the mid-40s, perhaps because of stress linked to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-life-balance-is-their-second-priority-work-is-their-first-b069aeee?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the demands of work and family</a> . That juggle, coupled with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/would-life-be-better-if-you-worked-less-3f49e69a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">little time for self-reflection</a> , leaves many people unsure how to approach their next chapter.</p><p> Instructors in midlife programs explore topics including psychological development in midlife and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/anti-ageism-workplace-language-biggest-school-district-368db30f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">ageism</a> , which can cause people to believe they are “irrelevant, over the hill, and that their best years are behind them,” said Conley.</p><p> He created MEA after working at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ABNB" class="">Airbnb</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> where the home-sharing company&#39;s young founders dubbed him a modern elder at age 52. The workshops aim to help participants learn to better navigate stressful transitions, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/layoffs-tech-job-cuts-fired-survival-guide-how-to-get-hired-laid-off-employees-11667943893?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">including layoffs</a> , divorce and the death of loved ones.</p><h3> Space for self-reflection</h3><p> Like the monthslong academic programs several universities have launched for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-60-000-these-colleges-help-older-workers-plot-encore-careers-a0060b9a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">adults nearing the end of careers</a> , most midlife courses bring together groups of eight to 50 people.</p><p> “These programs give people the space and structure to consider not just what, but who they want to be at this stage,” said Barbara Waxman,</p> a gerontologist who teaches at MEA.<p></p><p> Nadia Al Yafai, 46, said she discovered the Midlife ReThink, a $385 online program, after being laid off recently from a senior position at a UK insurer.</p><p> The Midlife ReThink proved transformational, she said, adding that meeting others who felt similarly unanchored comforted her. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824305?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A slide from the Midlife ReThink, which offers online classes to people seeking a new direction, outlines quarters of life.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Midlife Rethink</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Started in 2020 by Avivah Wittenberg-Cox, a coach and consultant who specializes in gender and generational balance in the workforce, the program consists of three 90-minute online sessions for about 25 participants.</p><p> “A lot of people suffer through transitions on their own, as if this is some terrible thing they are going through,” said Wittenberg-Cox. “Community is the key to helping people realize it&#39;s normal and fairly predictable at this age and stage to get restless” and crave change, she said.</p><p> Al Yafai said an exercise that asked her to define what she wants from the next seven years led her to start a consulting business.</p><p> “I went from feeling a bit lost at not being part of my old world anymore to realizing there&#39;s this new world of people doing really interesting things,” she said.</p><h3> &#39;We still have value&#39;</h3><p> Reboot Partners, which provides workshops and coaching on career and other transitions, has organized two weekend-long retreats this year, in Santa Fe, NM, and Sag Harbor, NY, for $1,895. Participants visualize their perfect life and discuss fears and motivations around change, said co-founder Jaye Smith. </p><p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824304?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Modern Elder Academy&#39;s virtual and in-person workshops held at its campus in Mexico aim to help participants better navigate stressful transitions.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Modern Elder Academy</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> On an oceanfront campus in Mexico&#39;s Baja California Sur, MEA teaches courses on re-creating careers, embracing midlife and optimizing longevity. It also offers weekslong online programs on transitions, purpose and reframing retirement for $395 to $1,250. It plans to open a campus in Santa Fe, NM, next year.</p><p> Lisa Fitzpatrick said MEA, which she first attended in 2019, helped her face down barriers to success.</p><p> Dr. Fitzpatrick, 55, was launching Grapevine Health, which publishes online health information for low-income communities. She relished the opportunity to interact with Conley, a veteran entrepreneur.</p><p> The Washington, DC, resident said an exercise to identify self-limiting beliefs helped her conquer a fear of being too old to start a business. She returned to Baja five times to attend workshops on entrepreneurship and healthcare. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="959" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824306?width=639&amp;height=959" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Lisa Fitzpatrick says attending Modern Elder Academy helped her confront her barriers to success.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ron Ceaser</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For that first visit, she received a scholarship for a seven-day stay that now costs $4,000 to $5,500.</p><p> One exercise Fitzpatrick particularly enjoys involves stacking rocks on the beach. “It sounds kind of woo-woo,” she said. But the task of balancing a big rock on a small one helped her overcome mental barriers to what she could achieve. “MEA helps people in midlife realize we still have value,” she said.</p><h3> Finding a purpose</h3><p> Some programs explore next acts or spirituality.</p><p> Dallas-based Halftime Institute&#39;s offerings include a two-day, $2,500 couples retreat and a $25,000 yearlong program. The latter features in-person and online sessions, as well as one-on-one coaching on relationships, health, faith and finding one&#39;s calling.</p><p> “Not everyone who goes through it is Christian but that&#39;s the perspective we come from,” said Co-Chief Executive Jim Stollberg. “We talk about a calling, rather than a purpose.”</p><p> For $2,500, Union Theological Seminary in New York offers a four-month Encore Transition program, with virtual sessions on topics such as spirituality in midlife and finding work with social purpose.</p><p> Consultant Carolyn Buck Luce leads a group of women through a weekslong online program called the Decade Game that costs $2,250. It challenges participants to set goals to guide their next decade in areas including education and purpose.</p><p> “It&#39;s about being able to declare the purpose you were called to,” said Luce.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How are you navigating midlife?加入下面的对话。</em> </p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/b28e0b44-8140-466a-922c-df1aa6d8aa70.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Write to Anne Tergesen at <a href="mailto:anne.tergesen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">anne.tergesen@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/midlife-crisis-money-business-companies-29dc2273</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/midlife-crisis-money-business-companies-29dc2273<author><![CDATA[Anne Tergesen]]></author><category> wsjlifework</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Career Planning/Management</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>Retirement Planning</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>career planning</category><category> management</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>retirement planning </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[New Ultrasound Therapy Could Help Treat Alzheimer’s, Cancer]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Sound waves combined with tiny bubbles in the bloodstream can push drugs into the brain and tough-to-reach tumors <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825729/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="French company Carthera has developed an ultrasound device to treat brain cancer. Shown here in a rendering, it works with tiny bubbles injected into the bloodstream to help drugs penetrate where they are needed." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> French company Carthera has developed an ultrasound device to treat brain cancer. Shown here in a rendering, it works with tiny bubbles injected into the bloodstream to help drugs penetrate where they are needed. Carthera <span>Carthera</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001068286"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001068286"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/denise-roland" itemprop="url" rel="author">Denise Roland</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 9:50 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ultrasound-therapy-alzheimers-cancer-treatment-862f1390"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Ultrasound, the decades-old technology known for giving early glimpses of unborn babies, could hold a key to a problem that has long challenged drug developers: getting medicines to hard-to-reach places to treat diseases like Alzheimer&#39;s and cancer.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> A cutting-edge approach that combines ultrasound waves with tiny bubbles of inert gas injected into the bloodstream can get more chemotherapy to tumor cells and enable drugs to breach one of the most stubborn frontiers in the human body—the blood-brain barrier. It is also being explored as a new way to deliver gene therapy.</p><p> “There&#39;s an extremely wide variety of where this sort of drug delivery or augmentation with ultrasound and bubbles can take us,” says Flemming Forsberg, professor of radiology and director of ultrasound physics at Thomas Jefferson University in Philadelphia. The effectiveness of drugs in treating diseases like cancer, Alzheimer&#39;s and Parkinson&#39;s is often limited by poor penetration into tissues, he says, whether in the brain or in tumors in other parts of the body.</p><h3> Getting Medicine to the Site</h3><p> To get to the places they are needed, many drugs must move from the bloodstream into surrounding tissue. The medicines have to travel through the thin walls of the capillaries, the body&#39;s smallest blood vessels, and reach the target cells. This is tougher in some parts of the body than others. Some tumors are surrounded by dense networks of connective tissue that are hard to penetrate. In the brain, the capillary-wall cells are so tightly packed that they form a barrier that the vast majority of drugs can&#39;t get through.</p><p> The new approach relies on targeted ultrasound waves that cause vibrations in tiny bubbles that are injected into the bloodstream. The resulting force—which some compare to the way an opera singer&#39;s voice can make a wine glass quiver and even shatter—disrupts the surrounding capillary walls and tissue, temporarily creating microscopic gaps that have been shown to ease the passage of drugs in early human studies. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825973?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Carthera&#39;s ultrasound-emitting device for the brain is embedded in titanium mesh.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Carthera</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Some key questions must be explored as research progresses into larger human studies, says Seung-Schik Yoo, a researcher at Brigham and Women&#39;s Hospital and associate professor of radiology at Harvard Medical School who has done work in this area. One is ensuring that the disruption doesn&#39;t cause any lasting damage to tissues. Another is figuring out how frequently the procedure can be applied—and if there is a limit to the number of applications.</p><p> The procedure takes place during drug dosing or soon after. Typically, the microbubbles are injected intravenously while ultrasound, similar to the type used for fetal imaging, is applied at the target site for around five minutes. In one cancer trial, for instance, the microbubbles and ultrasound are administered around an hour after chemotherapy begins, so that the drug is at a high concentration in the blood at the time of the procedure.</p><p> While the microbubbles flow throughout the bloodstream, the disruption in tissue only occurs in the part of the body exposed to the ultrasound wave. The effect is temporary, lasting for as little as an hour, and the microbubbles remain in the blood for only around five minutes. The tiny size of the bubbles means they don&#39;t pose a risk of causing dangerous blockages in blood vessels, researchers say.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> EXPLORE THE FUTURE OF EVERYTHING</h4><p> <em>The Future of Everything looks at the innovation and technology transforming the way we live, work and play, covering <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/whats-ahead-for-work-bd3a352d" target="_blank" class="icon none">the workplace</a> , <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/whats-ahead-for-health-5dccbfca" target="_blank" class="icon none">health</a> , <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/whats-ahead-for-energy-climate-19d48267" target="_blank" class="icon none">energy &amp; climate</a> and more.</em></p></div></div><p> The component technologies aren&#39;t new. Ultrasound has been used in medicine for more than half a century. Since the 1990s, microbubbles injected into the bloodstream have been widely used as a contrast agent to enhance images created by diagnostic ultrasound.</p><p> Scientists observed that ultrasound causes these bubbles to resonate and saw the potential for that force to aid drug delivery. In 2001, scientists at Harvard Medical School demonstrated that ultrasound plus microbubbles could <a href="https://pubs.rsna.org/doi/10.1148/radiol.2202001804" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">open the blood-brain barrier in rabbits</a> . In the years since, scientists have tested the approach in many types of animals, building up early evidence that it could boost drug uptake and lead to meaningful improvements like greater tumor shrinkage in cancer.</p><h3> Treatment for Brain Cancer</h3><p> Now early human trials are producing encouraging results. In a small <a href="https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lanonc/article/PIIS1470-2045(23)00112-2/fulltext" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">study of patients with glioblastoma</a> —a type of brain cancer—researchers found that using the technology in treatment with carboplatin, a powerful chemotherapy, resulted in six times the amount of the drug in brain tissue that was exposed to the targeted ultrasound compared with unexposed brain tissue. In patients treated with paclitaxel, another cancer drug, levels were 3.7 times higher where the procedure was applied. Under normal circumstances, both drugs are seldom used to treat brain cancer because so little can get across the blood-brain barrier, according to Adam Sonabend, associate professor of neurological surgery at Northwestern University, who was involved in the trial.</p><p> In the glioblastoma trial, a small device developed by French company Carthera was used to avoid the difficulty of passing ultrasound through the skull bone, which weakens the power of the sound waves, according to the company&#39;s chief scientific officer Michael Canney. The ultrasound emitting device is embedded in titanium mesh used to reconstruct a small gap in the skull after surgery to remove the tumor, and sits directly above the brain. It emits ultrasound waves when connected to a power source via a syringe-like mechanism. The bubbles and the drugs are injected into the arm by intravenous infusion.</p><p> Exact Therapeutics, a Norwegian company, recently told investors that liver tumors in two patients in a Phase 1 clinical trial that were exposed to ultrasound plus microbubbles during chemotherapy shrank more than those without the ultrasound. The trial is still under way at the Royal Marsden Hospital in London, and the results haven&#39;t yet been peer-reviewed.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Have you or friends and family encountered medical advances in treatment of disease? What was your experience?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> The company has developed a formulation of microbubbles mixed with tiny oil droplets. When exposed to a particular frequency of ultrasound, they combine to temporarily form slightly larger bubbles in capillaries near the target tissue. They press directly against the capillary walls and stay there for longer, strengthening and prolonging the disruptive effects that allow drugs to pass into the target tissue, according to Exact Therapeutics Chief Executive Per Walday.</p><h3> Avenue for Gene Therapy </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825974?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> San Francisco-based SonoThera is developing a technology that uses microbubbles and ultrasound to deliver gene therapies.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: SonoThera</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Another potential application of the new ultrasound approach is in gene therapy. Now, gene therapies rely on stripped-down viruses to carry and insert genetic material into target cells. A shortcoming of that approach is that the virus generates an immune response, so any repeat dose would be quickly destroyed by the body&#39;s defenses. Another limitation of viral vectors is that they can only carry genes up to a certain size. Animal studies suggest that ultrasound plus microbubbles could enable genetic material to pass into target cells without a viral carrier. San Francisco-based startup SonoThera is developing the technology with the aim of starting a Phase 1 clinical trial in 2025, the company&#39;s Chief Executive Kenneth Greenberg says.</p><p> An important area of work has been fine-tuning the size and shape of the ultrasound waves to bring about the right level of vibration for the target tissue in question, Greenberg says. “Much like a symphony, there is a complexity of different sounds and harmonics and amplitudes and timing that can be delivered through ultrasound,” he says. “The new twist is how you optimize the acoustics to maximize delivery for specific target organs.”</p><p> Ultrasound research could open up many new opportunities, say those involved. “This is just the beginning,” says Carthera&#39;s Canney. With this technology, he says, doctors can revisit many drugs that have performed poorly in the past and ask: “Is it the drug, or just that we&#39;re not getting the drug there?”</p><p> Write to <a href="mailto:future@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">future@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d0225ea7-8532-42a1-8c31-5b317282b95d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 13:50:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ultrasound-therapy-alzheimers-cancer-treatment-862f1390</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ultrasound-therapy-alzheimers-cancer-treatment-862f1390<author><![CDATA[Denise Roland]]></author><category> wsj future of everything</category><category> Pharmaceuticals</category><category> Cancer Drugs</category><category> Healthcare/Life Sciences</category><category> Specialized Drugs/Medications</category><category> Cancer</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Chemotherapy/Radiotherapy/Immunotherapy</category><category> Demographic Health</category><category>健康</category><category>Infant/Child/Teenage Health</category><category> Medical Conditions</category><category> Medical Treatments/Procedures</category><category> WSJ Future of Everything</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> cancer</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>chemotherapy</category><category> radiotherapy</category><category> immunotherapy</category><category> demographic health</category><category> health</category><category> infant</category><category> child</category><category> teenage health</category><category> medical conditions</category><category> medical treatments</category><category> procedures</category><category> pharmaceuticals</category><category> cancer drugs</category><category> healthcare</category><category> life sciences</category><category> specialized drugs</category><category> medications </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Hollywood’s Fight: How Much AI Is Too Much?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Studios see potential in the technology, while actors, writers and other industry workers fear the worst <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826143/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo Illustration by Emil Lendof/The Wall Street Journal <span>Photo Illustration by Emil Lendof/The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001095061"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001095061"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jessica-toonkel" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jessica Toonkel</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/amol-sharma" itemprop="url" rel="author">Amol Sharma</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 7:56 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/at-the-core-of-hollywoods-ai-fight-how-far-is-too-far-f57630df"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Alan Ruck, the actor who played Connor Roy in HBO&#39;s “Succession,” says he and a director friend tested out the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-ai-chatbot-app-explained-11675865177?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">generative-AI tool ChatGPT</a> a few months ago over lunch, to see whether it could write a screenplay.</p><p> They asked it to write a scene about Ruck as a soldier in basic training, a play on the actor&#39;s role in the Broadway show “Biloxi Blues.”</p><p> “It was s <em>—</em> ,” Ruck said. “It was every cliché and hackneyed idea you could imagine.”</p><p> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/podcasts/tech-news-briefing/ai-and-streaming-play-leading-roles-in-hollywood-strike/e0fbf61f-eaf4-41b4-b2a5-1f2f184c5636?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">potential use of artificial intelligence</a> in TV and movies has become a hot-button issue in the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hollywood-actors-set-to-join-writers-on-strike-after-contract-expires-d86e7f30?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">biggest Hollywood labor strike</a> in 60 years. Ruck, like many writers and actors on the picket lines, is worried the technology will replace jobs and produce low-quality content.</p><p> Entertainment executives say bots won&#39;t be penning scripts soon, calling such fears overblown. But big companies across Hollywood, including <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WBD" class="">Warner Bros. Discovery</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PARA" class="company-name">Paramount Global</a> and NBCUniversal, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-chatgpt-hollywood-intellectual-property-spongebob-81fd5d15?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">are already using AI tools</a> in other ways and are actively exploring new applications, from summarizing scripts to special-effects to promotional marketing, people familiar with the situation say. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826209?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Alan Ruck, who is seen in a scene from HBO&#39;s &#39;Succession,&#39; has raised concerns over AI tools.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: HBO/Everett Collection</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Several studio executives said AI tools could accelerate storyboarding, which uses a series of graphics to show how a story unfolds, and set design <strong>,</strong> such as dreaming up what a restaurant in the 1960s might look like. Producers could use <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-deepfakes-celebrity-marketing-brands-81381aa6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a digital replica</a> of an actor to make tweaks to a scene without having to reshoot it—to turn someone&#39;s head or change their expression slightly, studio executives said.</p><p> A promising application is for dubbing of actors&#39; voices in different languages. AI could make the audio sound like Ben Affleck or Harrison Ford in Italian or German and even adjust the movement of their lips accordingly.</p><p> Some production workers say this is all leading down a dangerous path. Harry Yoon, a film editor who has worked on such movies as “Minari” and “Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings,” said he is worried that AI models, if fed enough data, could create a decent first cut of a scene.</p><p> “Pretty soon executives will be asking, &#39;Why do we need three editors on a series? Why not two or one?&#39;” he said. Yoon said there is a value in the slow process of humans watching daily footage and hearing lines over and over. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=0B69A51F-2148-4479-9D5B-1AB9ABE390DC&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fat-the-core-of-hollywoods-ai-fight-how-far-is-too-far-f57630df&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Netflix co-Chief Executive Ted Sarandos said the company and other streaming platforms, studios and networks were &#39;super committed&#39; to reaching a deal with striking Hollywood actors and writers. Photo: Chris Delmas/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Entertainment giants have talked to a range of AI players, including OpenAI, text-to-video specialist Runway, image-generator Stability Diffusion and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ADBE" class="">Adobe</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span></p> as they explore how to put the technology to use. Entertainment executives say some jobs probably would be at risk as AI is woven into the production process, but in other cases it would just be a tool to make jobs easier.<p></p><p> “AI raises hard, important creative and legal questions for everyone,” said the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers, the group that negotiates on behalf of studios and streamers. “So it&#39;s something that requires a lot more discussion, which we&#39;re committed to doing.”</p><p> Warner has held discussions with OpenAI about using ChatGPT for tasks such as creating descriptions of shows on its Max streaming service and possibly, down the road, for summarizing scripts submitted to studio executives for review, according to people familiar with the situation.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NFLX" class="company-name">Netflix</a></p> is looking to hire an AI product manager who will “define the strategic vision for” the streamer&#39;s machine-learning platform, according to a job posting.<p></p><p> The labor unions involved in the strike—the Screen Actors Guild and Writers Guild of America— <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fran-drescher-nanny-actors-strike-sag-aftra-4477c7cd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">are pushing for better compensation</a> in the streaming era and to shore up their benefits. But they are also pushing for protections from the rise of AI tools.</p><p> “It isn&#39;t just a danger for creative labor in Hollywood. It&#39;s a danger for all labor everywhere,” said Ruck, who has been out on the picket lines. “If they can program AI to replace the creative jobs they will certainly be able to program it to replace middle-management jobs.”</p><p> AI company executives say the point of their tools isn&#39;t to replace creators, but to allow them to have more time doing the creative parts of their jobs. “We only hear horror stories and fairy tales,” said Cristóbal Valenzuela, chief executive of Runway. “It&#39;s much more nuanced than that…you can&#39;t just type in &#39;make me a movie,&#39; and it will create a movie.”</p><p> Chad Nelson, chief creative director at Topgolf Media, who recently created a short film with OpenAI&#39;s DALL-E tool, predicted AI tools will be replacing some creative jobs in Hollywood within one to two years. “The idea that you need to secure a drone shot on the Pacific Coast Highway at sunset with a specific color car and the light in a certain way, won&#39;t be a thing people will have to do anymore,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="394" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826210?width=700&amp;height=394" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> AI tools were used for work on the film &#39;Everything Everywhere All at Once,&#39; which stars Michelle Yeoh.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: David Bornfriend/A24/Everett Collection</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Evan Halleck, a visual-effects specialist who used Runway&#39;s tools to work on the Oscar-winning film “Everything Everywhere All at Once,” said he loves that these tools allowed him to reduce some of the more tedious work in his job. However, he said, “I have fears that a 10-day gig might become a five-day gig.”</p><p> AI tools already can handle some work done by concept designers, who are hired by studios to help illustrate a scene. “The thing that sucks about the visual-effects industry as opposed to writers or actors is we don&#39;t have a union,” said Bilali Mack, a visual-effects supervisor who recently worked with Brendan Fraser on the Oscar-winning movie, “The Whale.”</p><p> Mark Patch, a former visual-effects production worker, said he is trying to organize people in a union for entertainment industry workers.</p><p> The Motion Pictures Editors Guild is addressing AI and how it could affect its members in a coming report, according to a letter the group sent to its members earlier in July.</p><p> The Screen Actors Guild says it wants to ensure studios obtain “informed consent” from actors before using digital replicas of them, and offer talent fair compensation. The Writers Guild of America has said it wants to clearly define that “source material” and “literary material,” which its members get compensated for, cannot be generated by AI tools. The Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers has said it has made robust and fair proposals addressing those concerns.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What role should AI play in the entertainment industry?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> To address the issue of consent, a startup called Vaisual is creating databases of actors who have given the company permission to have their photos taken and be part of its AI model.</p><p> Entertainment executives said they would be open to writers using AI technologies as a tool to help them brainstorm and develop stories, but the idea of bots replacing human writers is far-fetched.</p><p> “Generative AI can generate a lot of ideas but it can&#39;t tell the difference between a good idea and a bad idea,” said Jon Dudkowski, a director of the Paramount+ series “Star Trek: Discovery.”</p><p> Some actors and writers are worried that if they don&#39;t take a hard line now on AI, when it is in its infancy, it will be too late.</p><p> “The AI technology we have right now is the worst it will ever be in our lifetimes, which is why it&#39;s important right now to define if it is its own creative entity or whether it&#39;s a tool for creatives to use,” said producer and writer Dahlia Heyman, who <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/streaming-brought-hollywood-to-a-standstill-now-comes-the-pain-3afcbb68?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">was picketing at Netflix</a> on a recent afternoon.</p><p> Leif Gantvoort, an actor who has worked on shows such as “NCIS” and “SWAT,” said he is more concerned about compensation issues than AI. “That is a wave that&#39;s on its way,” he said. “To stand in its way—I just don&#39;t see it as the primary concern.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826212?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The potential use of AI in TV and movies has become a hot-button issue in the biggest Hollywood labor strike in 60 years.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: caroline brehman/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> —Tom Dotan contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Jessica Toonkel at <a href="mailto:jessica.toonkel@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jessica.toonkel@wsj.com</a> and Amol Sharma at <a href="mailto:Amol.Sharma@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Amol.Sharma@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/45b711d0-d12b-4ed4-89ff-24783c6b1fa4.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 11:56:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/at-the-core-of-hollywoods-ai-fight-how-far-is-too-far-f57630df</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/at-the-core-of-hollywoods-ai-fight-how-far-is-too-far-f57630df<author><![CDATA[Jessica ToonkelAmol Sharma]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>Broadcasting</category><category> Television Broadcasting</category><category> Cable Broadcasting</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>技术</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Labor Disputes</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Celebrities</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>Feature Films</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>电影</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>Theater</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Warner Bros. Discovery Inc. Series A</category><category> WBD</category><category> Paramount Global</category><category> PARA</category><category> Warner Bros. Discovery</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>labor disputes</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>celebrities</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>feature films</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>电影</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>theater</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>broadcasting</category><category> television broadcasting</category><category> cable broadcasting</category><category>媒体</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Local Malls, Stuck in ‘Death Spiral,’ Plunge in Value]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Crystal Mall in Connecticut, worth $150 million in 2012, recently sold for $9.5 million <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823519/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="The cut-rate sales price of Crystal Mall in Waterford, Conn., shows how fast the fortunes of U.S. regional malls have fallen in recent years." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> The cut-rate sales price of Crystal Mall in Waterford, Conn., shows how fast the fortunes of US regional malls have fallen in recent years. Johnny Milano/Bloomberg News <span>Johnny Milano/Bloomberg News</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093483"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093483"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kate-king" itemprop="url" rel="author">Kate King</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> WATERFORD, Conn.—Crystal Mall&#39;s parking lots used to be so crowded that parents would line up to drop off their teenagers near one of the entrances rather than search for a spot.</p><p> Now, the vast stretches of cracked pavement surrounding this 1980s-era regional mall on Connecticut&#39;s coast have more weeds than cars. Valued by an appraiser at $153 million as recently as 2012, Crystal Mall sold in June for just over $9.5 million in a foreclosure auction.</p><p> “To look at it now, it&#39;s disheartening,” said Waterford&#39;s top elected leader, First Selectman Rob Brule, who grew up in this working-class town and described the mall as the social centerpiece of his youth.</p><p> Crystal Mall&#39;s cut-rate sales price shows how rapidly the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/shopping-mall-nostalgia-auction-420a44f9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">value of America&#39;s regional malls</a> has deteriorated in recent years due to changing shopping habits, competition from other retail and the rise of online shopping.</p><p> Older, low-end malls are worth at least 50% and in some cases more than 70% less than they were when mall valuations peaked in late 2016, said Vince Tibone, head of US retail and industrial research for real-estate research firm Green Street.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Now, as more than $14 billion of loans backed by these properties comes due in the next 12 months, according to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MCO" class="company-name">Moody&#39;s</a> Analytics, struggling malls are defaulting on their debt. With mortgage rates up sharply, refinancing that debt will be more challenging and expensive.</p><p> About a fifth of all malls financed through commercial mortgage-backed securities are underwater, meaning the properties are worth less than the loans they back, said Kevin Fagan, head of commercial real-estate economic analysis for Moody&#39;s.</p><p> In some cases, they are worth a lot less. Crystal Mall&#39;s former owner, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SPG" class="">Simon Property Group</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> stopped making payments on $81 million in outstanding CMBS debt during the pandemic and last year handed back the keys to the property it had owned since 1999.</p><p> The loan—which was included in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/carl-icahn-placing-a-big-bet-against-mall-owners-11574201244?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the CMBX 6 index</a> shorted by famous investor Carl Icahn —is expected to liquidate at a $70 million loss, or about 87% of the outstanding balance, according to Moody&#39;s.</p><p> Similar stories are playing out across the country. In Indiana, Muncie Mall backs a $31 million loan but is worth only $6 million after a March appraisal, according to Trepp. The 52-year-old mall was appraised at $73 million nine years ago and nearly fully occupied as recently as 2018.</p><p> Woodbridge Center, a 1.1 million-square-foot mall in central New Jersey, was appraised at $86 million earlier this year, a 76% drop from its last prepandemic appraisal in 2014, according to Trepp. The mall is in foreclosure on two CMBS loans, with outstanding balances totaling nearly a quarter-billion dollars. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826219?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “We&#39;ve seen dozens and dozens of malls liquidated at losses or had their values cut,” said Manus Clancy, senior managing director at Trepp.</p><p> Not all malls are on the brink of disaster. Newer, well-located properties with strong tenant rosters are generating healthy foot traffic and returns for investors. But even these high-quality malls have declined in value by an estimated 50% since 2016, Tibone said, making malls one of the worst performing commercial real-estate sectors over that period.</p><p> Widespread <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/retail-chains-shed-stores-but-it-isnt-good-for-business-11605436204?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">department-store closures</a> beginning in 2018 hastened malls&#39; decline. Large mall anchors like</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/M" class="">Macy&#39;s</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> Bon-Ton, JCPenney and Sears closed about 875 department stores between 2018 and the end of 2020, according to Green Street, compared with a combined 175 in 2016 and 2017.<p></p><p> “It really accelerated the death spiral of the industry,” Tibone said. “You start losing department stores, that causes sales and traffic at the center to decline. Then more tenants leave. It starts this awful cycle.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C72EA178-F0CA-46FE-B63D-3CE629CAF70C&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Flocal-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The pandemic has changed the way we shop. More people buying things online means more people returning things, too. WSJ&#39;s Dalvin Brown explains how some companies are leveraging gig workers to make those returns for you. Photo illustration: David Fang<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The death spiral at the Crystal Mall started in 2018, when anchor tenant <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sears-exit-would-leave-big-holes-in-malls-some-landlords-welcome-that-1539342000?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Sears declared bankruptcy</a> and announced plans to close. Macy&#39;s shut its location three years later. Overall revenue at Crystal Mall declined 39% between 2018 and 2022, while expenses fell only 10%, according to Trepp.</p><p> “All the stores used to be open, and everything used to be nice and beautiful,” said Melissa Rodriguez, 40 years old, standing outside the mall&#39;s food court one recent afternoon.</p><p> Now, many of the shops have closed. One of her favorite stores, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BBBYQ" class="">Bed Bath &amp; Beyond</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> is shutting its location after <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/some-investors-arent-giving-up-on-bed-bath-beyond-7c1dcd37?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">declaring bankruptcy</a> earlier this year. Before the pandemic, Rodriguez said, she often visited the mall twice a week but now comes only once a month.</p><p> “It&#39;s not like before,” she said.</p><p> Christmas Tree Shops, which shared an anchor space with Bed Bath &amp; Beyond, is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/christmas-tree-shops-to-liquidate-all-stores-ea53da39?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">also closing following bankruptcy</a> . Once those retailers vacate, JCPenney will be the only anchor tenant left at Crystal Mall. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823825?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Crystal Mall fell into decline following closings of two anchor stores, Sears and Macy&#39;s, in recent years.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Johnny Milano/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Brule, Waterford&#39;s first selectman, said he would like to see the property redeveloped into a mixed-use site. He envisions a hotel for tourists visiting nearby Mystic and housing for local firefighters and teachers as well as employees of the local submarine manufacturer, General Dynamics Electric Boat. Maybe a hockey rink or a bowling alley, somewhere for the town&#39;s teenagers to gather.</p><p> “That&#39;s what this property could be,” Brule said.</p><p> It is unlikely these dreams for Crystal Mall will be realized under its new owner, New York-based investment firm Namdar Realty Group. A company executive told Brule during an introductory call that it doesn&#39;t redevelop properties, Brule said.</p><p> Namdar Chief Executive Igal Namdar said the company plans to implement an “aggressive leasing strategy to attract a mix of national and local tenants” to Crystal Mall.</p><p> Write to Kate King at <a href="mailto:kate.king@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">kate.king@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d<author><![CDATA[Kate King]]></author><category> wsj-usnews</category><category> commercial re</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> Retail/Wholesale</categor